        {
          "id": "in-hand-object-reorientation",
          "title": "In-Hand Reorienting",
          "shortDescription": "Change the orientation of a small rectangular prism from a stable grasp to another stable grasp.",
          "description": "Change the orientation of a small rectangular prism from a stable grasp at any orientation relative to the palm to a stable grasp at any other orientation.",
          "justification": "In-Hand Reorienting evaluates a system's ability to manipulate an object within the hand while maintaining continuous control and without relying on environmental support. The task involves quasistatic direct manipulation of a rigid object whose dimensions are comparable to those of the fingers and requires coordinated control of multiple finger joints to change the object's orientation relative to the palm. The task exhibits high constraint complexity, as successful completion depends on coordinating multiple simultaneous contacts, regulating grasp forces, and managing object motion within the hand. More broadly, in-hand reorientation is widely regarded as a hallmark capability of dexterous manipulation and serves as a canonical benchmark for evaluating the intrinsic manipulation capabilities of multifingered robotic hands.",
