          "justification": "Zipping a Zipper evaluates a system's ability to manipulate an articulated mechanism while interacting with both rigid and deformable components. The task involves quasistatic direct manipulation of a small zipper pull whose dimensions are significantly smaller than those of the hand, while simultaneously managing the motion and tension of the surrounding fabric. The task exhibits substantial constraint complexity, as successful completion depends on maintaining alignment between mating zipper components while operating within the mechanical constraints imposed by the zipper mechanism. It also involves significant constraint change, progressing engagement and disengagement as the zipper is closed and reopened. Because successful operation depends on coordinated interaction between rigid zipper elements, deformable fabric, and the hand, the task requires careful management of multiple simultaneous contacts throughout the manipulation sequence. More broadly, zipper manipulation serves as a representative benchmark for contact-rich interaction with articulated everyday objects and evaluates a manipulator's ability to coordinate manipulation of both rigid and deformable components.",
